Julian Savea will aim to continue his astonishing scoring streak against England at Twickenham on Saturday, having been feted as ‘better’ than Jonah Lomu — his childhood idol.

Last month, All Blacks coach Steve Hansen suggested that his team’s supreme finisher had become a more deadly threat than Lomu, who terrorised England at the 1995 World Cup. Savea has certainly demonstrated a greater scoring knack, having touched down 29 times in 30 Tests.

He is on course to be the most predatory accumulator of tries in the history of the international game — eclipsing Lomu and other Kiwi icons such as Doug Howlett and Christian Cullen.

